{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f0d3e945-83e6-4fd5-bb56-b9b118b1088b","content":"On macOS, crash information is available in two forms:\n\n**1. Crash Reports (automatic)**\nmacOS generates `.ips` crash reports automatically:\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nYou can also view them in **Console.app** → Crash Reports. These contain the stack trace, exception type, and faulting thread.\n\n**2. Core Dumps (opt-in)**\nmacOS disables core dumps by default. To enable them *before* running your app:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo mkdir -p /cores\nsudo chmod 1777 /cores\n```\nCore files will be written to `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can then inspect with `lldb`:\n```bash\nlldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./your-app\n```\n\nFor most NativeAOT crashes, the `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is the quickest starting point.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0147a4b2-be0d-4182-8dd2-ab6b6ce871f4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's where to find them:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports**: Located in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user-level) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-level).\n2. **Console.app**: You can also view them via the Console app under \"Crash Reports.\"\n\n\n3. **Core dumps**: macOS disables core dumps by default, but you can enable them by running `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching the app, which will write them to `/cores/`.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"9420:262085:187B039:1BD1FDE:69E81F8F"},"id":"6d1debd5-09fc-471f-8030-c6ac2cc333c1","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:08:42.880Z","parentId":"54bed035-9fdb-4a1f-a525-2547757a821b"}
